WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Hi everyone, my name is Winston Chang and I'm a software engineer at Posit.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Today I'm going to talk about Shiny Express for Python.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Shiny Express is a new way of writing Shiny applications that lets you create web apps even more quickly and easily than before.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.000
First off, let's have a quick overview of what Shiny is.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Shiny is a framework for writing interactive web applications with R and more recently with Python.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:32.000
It's focused particularly on data-driven applications, so if you want to create a data dashboard that shows real-time data,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:39.000
or if you want to create a web app that lets users interact with and explore a dataset, Shiny is a great tool for doing that.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:45.000
And you don't need to know HTML, JavaScript, and CSS to create a powerful, attractive application with Shiny.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
The idea is that with Shiny, you can just do this with Python code.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:59.000
For this presentation, I'm going to talk about Shiny in the context of Python, because I'm talking about Shiny Express and Shiny Express is currently just for Python.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:09.000
Before Shiny Express, we had Shiny, just Shiny, which we're now calling Shiny Core to help distinguish between that and Shiny Express.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Shiny Express is a more concise, easier-to-use syntax for writing Shiny applications, but it's based on the same technology as Shiny Core.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
We'll see how to get started with Shiny Express and create your first Shiny app,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:28.000
and then I'll show you how to deploy applications to Posit Connect, which is a hosting platform that runs on a server in your organization,

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.000
or deploy to Shinyapps.io, which is a hosted server from Posit where you don't have to manage your own server.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.000
All right, let's just take a look at some examples of what you can do with Shiny.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:46.000
So here's one that shows air pollution data at different points in time.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:52.000
If we go all the way back to the 90s, you can see there's just a lot more air pollution back then,

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
and we can select different data sources.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Then there's also, we can interact with the filtering here to show different ranges of years of data to show,

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.000
and as we can see over time, deaths have just been decreasing air pollution.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Here's another example. It's an educational example, and it demonstrates how a parameter,

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
adjusting a parameter can change this coefficient estimates.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Change this, you can see the plot updates, and scroll down, there's some educational content here on this page,

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.000
and then there's some more plots that were affected by that slider from up above.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Here's a simulation of the motion of the Earth and Moon and a hypothetical planet X.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:42.000
All right, so if we can adjust some of these parameters for the way that simulation works,

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.000
then run the simulation, then you can see how those things move,

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:54.000
and we can adjust the parameters here, like change the starting speed of the Earth and the direction of motion,

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:59.000
and then rerun the simulation and see how things would be different.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
And finally, here's one more. It's a data dashboard for exploring data.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:10.000
In this case, it's data about tips at a restaurant.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:22.000
So we could just look at data from lunches, data from dinners, and change the range of the restaurant bills,

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:29.000
and we can look at this data table here and sort based on the gender of the person who paid.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:35.000
So let's get started. To get started for learning, I suggest you use ShinyLive.io,

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
which lets you run Shiny without having to install anything on your computer.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
So we're going to start here. This is the main Shiny website.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:49.000
We'll click on Shiny for Python, and then we'll click on Playground,

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.000
and then this will take you to ShinyLive.io.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Or you can just type ShinyLive.io in their location bar, and you'll go straight to this page.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
I'm going to close these because I already have what I want opened.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
What we have here is a very basic Shiny application.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:15.000
This is sort of the minimal Shiny application that will do anything in response to the user's input.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:22.000
So we've got a slider here, and then we've got this text here that changes in response to the slider.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So n times 2 is 40, move the slider, 52, n times 2 is 104.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Great. Now let's take a look at the Python code for this.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:38.000
So we say up here, from Shiny Express, import some things here,

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.000
and then we say UI.inputSlider,

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:49.000
n, this is a label that tells Python how to access the value later,

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:55.000
and capital N, that's the text label up here, and then the minimum, maximum, and the starting value.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
That makes the slider appear in the app.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And then next we have this thing here, which is a render text.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:14.000
It's a decorator, which makes text show up in the application.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
We say def text, we just give this some name.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
The name of the function is just txt.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:28.000
And this returns a string, but this string, the code for this, it accesses input.n.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
So when we say input.n, that actually refers to this n over here.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
So input.n times 2.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
And then we can, you know, if we comment this out, for example,

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.000
and then rerun the app, we'll just hit the play button,

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.000
then it just doesn't show up there in the app.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:50.000
All right, so now I'm going to uncomment, rerun, and it shows up again.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And we can just, you know, we can play around with this,

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:58.000
we can change these values to n times 100, and rerun that.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
Okay.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Now, this is the app written in Shiny Express,

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.000
and here's the same app written in Shiny Core.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:14.000
So as you can see, there's a bit more code involved for Shiny Core.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:20.000
Let's take a quick comparison between the code for Shiny Express and Shiny Core.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
Okay, so this is for Shiny Express.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:29.000
You can see the code is quite a bit shorter, and this is the code for Shiny Core.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
Now, for Shiny Express, we just would declare a slider,

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
and it would show up on the page, and we'd declare this render text,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.000
and that would also just show up on the page.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:43.000
For Shiny Core, it's a bit different.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:49.000
Well, first off, we're importing from Shiny instead of importing from Shiny Express.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:56.000
Also, we need to create the UI completely separately from the server logic application.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:04.000
So you create this thing called app UI, and it consists of UI.pageFluid,

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
which is just sort of a page-level wrapper for all the content.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
And then inside of that, we have these nested function calls for other components.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:18.000
So one of them is UIInputSlider, which is the same as for Shiny Express.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:24.000
But then we also had to add this output text, and we pass it the string txt.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:32.000
So this output text wasn't necessary in Shiny Express, but we needed to put it in Shiny Core.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:41.000
Now, this whole UI here, this creates HTML that gets sent to the web browser.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.000
All right, so the next main component is the server logic.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:49.000
So we say def server. This is a function.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:52.000
It takes input, output, and session as parameters.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.000
And then we do the same thing that we did in the Shiny Express app,

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:01.000
where we say render text and give it this function.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:08.000
Now, this txt, the name of this function, corresponds to this txt over here.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:13.000
If these didn't match, then nothing would show up in the web application.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
So it's very important that those are the same.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.000
OK, so we've got our UI and the server components,

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:24.000
and then we put them together and save it in a variable named app.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
All right, so this is how we do it here.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:30.000
We just pass it to this capital A app function.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:35.000
All right, so you can see there's more code involved for Shiny Core,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.000
but it's a bit more structured.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
And that can be useful in some cases,

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.000
but if you want to be able to create an app quickly

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
and with a minimum of fuss,

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:49.000
then Shiny Express is going to be the way to go.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.000
All right, now back in the Shiny live interface,

